      <h2>Understanding Volume Units</h2>
      <p>
        Volume measures three-dimensional space. The metric system uses the cubic meter as the base unit, while the imperial system primarily uses cubic feet. Liters and gallons are practical units derived from these cubic measurements. One cubic meter is exactly 1,000 liters, and one cubic foot is approximately 28.317 liters. Understanding these relationships is essential for construction, shipping, HVAC, aquariums, and any field that deals with capacity or displacement.
      </p>
      <p>
        This converter supports seven common volume units and converts between all of them instantly. Enter a value in any unit, and the results show the equivalent in every other unit.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Cubic Feet vs. Cubic Meters</h2>
      <p>
        One cubic meter equals approximately 35.315 cubic feet. One cubic foot equals approximately 0.02832 cubic meters. These conversions come up frequently in international construction and engineering, where project specifications may use one system while materials are measured in another. For quick mental estimates, think of a cubic meter as roughly 35 cubic feet or about the volume of a large refrigerator.
      </p>

      <h3>Cubic Yards for Bulk Materials</h3>
      <p>
        One cubic yard equals 27 cubic feet (3 x 3 x 3 feet) or approximately 0.7646 cubic meters. Concrete, mulch, gravel, topsoil, and sand are typically sold by the cubic yard in the United States. Knowing how to convert between cubic yards and cubic meters or cubic feet helps when comparing international supplier quotes or working with metric construction specifications.
      </p>

      <h3>Liters and Gallons</h3>
      <p>
        One liter equals 0.001 cubic meters or 0.0353 cubic feet. A US gallon is 3.785 liters while a UK (imperial) gallon is 4.546 liters. The difference between US and UK gallons matters when comparing fuel economy figures, tank capacities, or recipe quantities from different countries. Always verify which gallon standard is being used.
      </p>
<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How many cubic feet are in a cubic meter?</h3>
      <p>
        One cubic meter equals approximately 35.3147 cubic feet. Conversely, one cubic foot equals approximately 0.0283168 cubic meters. This conversion is commonly needed in construction, shipping, and HVAC calculations.
      </p>

      <h3>How do I convert cubic feet to liters?</h3>
      <p>
        Multiply the number of cubic feet by 28.3168 to get liters. For example, 10 cubic feet equals approximately 283.168 liters. This conversion is useful when comparing container volumes, aquarium sizes, or storage capacities.
      </p>

      <h3>What is the difference between cubic feet and cubic yards?</h3>
      <p>
        One cubic yard equals 27 cubic feet (3 feet x 3 feet x 3 feet). Cubic yards are commonly used for measuring bulk materials like concrete, mulch, gravel, and soil, while cubic feet are used for smaller volumes like refrigerator capacity and room air volume.
      </p>

      <h3>How many gallons are in a cubic foot?</h3>
      <p>
        One cubic foot equals approximately 7.481 US gallons or 6.229 UK (imperial) gallons. US and UK gallons are different sizes: a US gallon is 3.785 liters while a UK gallon is 4.546 liters.
      </p>

      <h3>How many liters are in a cubic meter?</h3>
      <p>
        One cubic meter equals exactly 1,000 liters. This is an exact conversion by definition, since one liter is defined as one cubic decimeter (0.001 cubic meters). This makes converting between liters and cubic meters straightforward.
      </p>

